  "summary": "Mr. Merdle, the lawyer for Leonard Walpole, visits Mrs. Mogson to obtain information that might clarify his client's guilt or innocence. Mrs. Mogson, who has a severe facial scar caused by sulphuric acid, expresses a desire for revenge against a woman who \"took\" her lover. She initially demands two hundred pounds for information, but Merdle negotiates the price down to twenty pounds. In exchange, she provides a bundle of love letters written by Roman Hergel to a man named Max. The most recent letter is dated the day Leonard was arrested.\n\nThe letters suggest that Roman Hergel lied in court regarding her whereabouts at 10:20 PM. To verify this, Merdle visits a cinema on Lyon Road, where a guard confirms that Roman and a man were at the theater during that time. Merdle realizes that Roman fabricated her testimony out of personal animosity.\n\nDuring the trial for the murder of Emily French, the defense presents the letters as evidence. The correspondence reveals Roman's true motive: she intended to frame Leonard to achieve revenge, even writing that she would claim he arrived home covered in blood. Upon the reading of the letters, Roman admits she fabricated her entire story and confesses that Leonard had actually arrived home at 9:20 PM, as he had originally claimed.",
